A Republican strategy to hinder Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to fight electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth and claims that electoral fraud is less prevalent in the United States than the number of people who die from lightning strikes.
In fact, Republican lawyers have found no more than 300 cases of election fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In that sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike in Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
And in the same vein, a majority of U.S. governments enacted, from 2009, new laws that made it difficult to register or vote.
This phenomenon has spread after the November 2010 elections, which saw the increase of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, during 2011, 180 bills restricting the exercise of the right to vote were introduced in 41 states.
New electoral laws require voters to present an identity document with a photograph, in addition to proof of U.S. citizenship.
On the other hand, these laws reduce early voting periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on polling day, and withdraw their right to vote from citizens with a criminal record.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
The state of Indiana was the first to demand it.
The U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of Indiana law in 2008.
Therefore, the Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
In recent years, these authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity card, such as a Social Security card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, that is, 21 million people of voting age, do not have any photo ID issued by a state government agency.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identity card with these characteristics.
But, often, obtaining the required identity document costs more than a hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African-Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000 a year, 18% of citizens over the age of 65 and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have a photo ID.
And there's more.
In many states, students, the voters who vote the most for Democratic candidates, cannot use the photo ID issued by their institution.
On the other hand, those same states authorize members of fishing or hunting clubs that usually vote for Republican parties to use the documents issued by those clubs.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to make such a demand.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are American citizens.
These measures clearly seek to limit the Hispanic vote.
It seems that two out of three Hispanic voters support the Democratic Party.
On the other hand, Republican lawmakers backed in 2011 certain laws abolishing voter registration on the same day of polling in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to create a support service for voters who wished to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns contributed to the registration of about 10 million citizens.
Measures taken since 2009 resulted in a drop in the registration rate of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers passed laws in five other states that favored shortening the pre-voting period.
For example, in the 2008 Florida election, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African Americans, while the latter represented only 13% of the state's voters.
In the case of Hispanics it was exactly the same.
These represent only 11% of the electorate, which is equivalent to 24% of citizens who vote in advance.
However, whites, who make up 76% of the electorate, make up only 46% of citizens who vote in advance.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters have fiercely opposed the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
In this regard, Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The U.S. Attorney’s Office stepped in to suspend the most controversial laws.
It was possible, in part, to limit the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states passed the law requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted on, as it is clear that they are intended to influence the results of 2012 in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that states that have passed such laws account for 171 of the 270 votes needed in the electoral college to achieve the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty whether these legislative changes to the electoral system will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, the measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Prostate Cancer Screening: Doing the Test or Not?
In fact, the PSA test sometimes presents erroneous results, with false negative results or even false positive results, after which it is decided to perform useless medical interventions.
It is more than enough reason to make men, already reluctant by themselves, doubt whether or not screening tests should be done.
To take the test or not?
We asked for advice from two specialists.
Studies conducted in the United States found a high rate of contagion among sample groups, making it difficult to interpret these data and make strong recommendations.
For its part, the European study showed some difference in mortality between patients who had been screened and those who did not.
The study, with a follow-up at 12 years, also showed that there is between 30 and 40% chance of suffering metastases if the screening test has not been performed.
I therefore recommend testing from the age of 50, or from the age of 40 if your father has suffered from prostate cancer.
Men of African-American descent have a higher risk index.
The key is to make a good decision once the cancer is detected.
There are aggressive cancers and other cancers that are indolent.
It is really necessary to make the patient understand the degree of risk of their cancer. All possible options should be offered and not necessarily treat prostate cancers that do not threaten long-term life, in which case you should rather opt for active surveillance of the disease.
Today, many men who have been diagnosed with cancer are left untreated, as cancer is not aggressive or life-threatening.
Instead, we suggest active surveillance of the disease and, if it progresses, we offer treatment.
We are increasingly determining precise criteria for deciding who should or should not be treated.
I recommend that the test be done in any case.
But it is important that you talk to your doctor to determine whether or not the test should be done.
Movember has created, in collaboration with the International Society of Urology, a tool to evaluate the pros and cons of the PSA test.
This document can be downloaded (for the time being in English only, but translations will be offered shortly) at the following address: http://en.movember.com/fr/mens-health/prostate-cancer-screening
Preventing the disease
Unfortunately, there is no miracle recipe for preventing cancer.
Despite progress in research, adopting healthy lifestyle habits is still the best way to reduce the risks of suffering from the disease.
We estimate that if everyone ate well and moved enough, 30% of cancers could be prevented.
“If no one smoked, that rate would rise to at least 50%,” said André Beaulieu, spokesman for the Canadian Cancer Society.
Instead, we estimate that about 10% of cancers are hereditary.
Many others remain totally inexplicable.
For the Canadian Cancer Society, the fight against smoking remains a priority despite the decline in the number of smokers.
Tobacco is linked to 85% of lung cancer cases.
It is also a risk factor for other types of cancer.
It greatly harms people’s health.
“Today, there are still 1.5 million smokers in Quebec,” said spokesman André Beaulieu.
10 years after quitting smoking, the risk of dying from cancer is halved.
The weight
Fat and obesity also favor the onset of the disease, according to the SCC.
They increase the risks of cancer of the breast, colon, rectum, esophagus, pancreas, and uterus.
"Research shows that regular, lifelong physical activity protects against breast cancer," they add.
The Food
The body also recommends limiting the consumption of red meat.
In large quantities, they escalate the risks of colorectal cancer.
Dairy products should also be avoided.
Preserving meat for smoking, drying or salting can lead to the formation of carcinogens.
"They can damage the cells of the body and lead to the development of cancer," they explain.
The Vitamins
In recent years, several scientists have studied the links between vitamin complexes and cancer.
However, at the moment their investigations are not conclusive.
According to the SCC, studies about vitamin E are contradictory.
While in one of them there was a decrease in prostate cancer risks, in another what was observed was, rather, an increase.
The effect of vitamin D on cancer has also not been clearly determined.
On the other hand, M. Beaulieu insists on the importance of discussing one’s concerns and family history with one’s doctor.
"Doing the screening test does not cause cancer."
The Higgs boson in detail
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson generated a big shock last summer, and rightly so.
It is believed, in fact, that this boson is part of the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything that exists in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
What’s more, it’s about the particle whose existence the standard model predicted: our best or “least bad” explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has not yet been empirically observed.
But for physicists it is not entirely clear that it is Higgs.
We know without a doubt that there is a new particle and that it closely resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at a major physics congress held in Kyoto seem to confirm that it is, although more data is still missing to be completely sure.
Anyway, we assume it's about Higgs, since the chances of making a mistake seem small. We'll see what it is about.
There is, in this great world, a general and inescapable law which implies that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There’s no way to break that rule and don’t try too hard, because you’ll end up hurting yourself.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also in it a law of these characteristics: the Pauli exclusion principle, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; a "state" consisting, roughly speaking, of some of its characteristics.
Physicists classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand we find the good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey the principle of Pauli.
And on the other hand there are the bosons, a dirty panda of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means they can be in the same place and at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure of Berkeley Laboratories, which, by the way, is extraordinary, bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons, which we will not talk about here, and the "force particles", by which the great forces of nature propagate and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, one might underline here, are not the exotic bugs we might believe.
In fact, if he manages to read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon or the "particle of light" that acts as a "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disorders" the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a bit like when we throw a stone at a pond.
In this "disorder" an electromagnetic wave (from light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing but a photon; that is, one of the "force-bearing" bosons.
More stable field
The same is true of the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, which needs to be "disordered" for this boson to appear.
Now, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field. To activate it, you need to reach extremely high energies, a little like an icy pond in which only a thick rock could slide over the surface.
That’s why it takes a huge particle accelerator like CERN’s (the big hadron collider is a ring 27 km in circumference!) to reach such energy levels.
The electromagnetic field analogy is a new tool that explains the relationship between Higgs and mass.
In fact, not all particles and materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never stand by itself glued to the door of a refrigerator.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the rest (like the photon, by the way), do not.
Now, what "can" all these investigations "bring?" asks Mrs. Plamondon.
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the standard model (MS), and also allows physicists to scrutinize the differences between the observations and predictions of the MS.
For their part, many fervently wish to find each other, as the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" that plugs certain holes in the model.
This, it must be said, still has enormous deficiencies, such as that it does not propose any explanation regarding gravity (ups!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter of the Universe (other ups!).
But we haven’t found such differences at CERN so far.
Repercussions
The repercussions of such investigations in our day-to-day lives are difficult to predict, but we do not think we are mistaken in saying that it will have none.
In the early 1960s, the pioneers of lasers in laboratories did not suspect at all the revolution that their work would provoke.
They glimpsed the scientific applications, but nothing more.
In fact, as the physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who developed the first continuous laser (the first ones were pulsed) in 1962, said, at first the laser was rather considered a "laboratory apparatus."
Just imagine...
And in addition, applications can also come from all the instrumentation surrounding the research.
For example, Willard Boyle himself developed a light collector in 1969 in the course of his research on optics.
Although it was not at all its original intention, this pickup now serves as an "eye" for all the digital devices in the world, which earned it the Nobel Prize in physics in 2009.
That doesn’t mean, of course, that the activities of the LHC necessarily want to transform our lives, but you never know...
Palliative care. The best way to die... <0x7C> Le Devoir
In its Commission Dying with Dignity, Quebec recently discussed the delicate question of the end of life.
The debate should resume soon while a bill is being prepared.
Now, within that essential domain, there is still much to be done.
Le Devoir has tried to see it up close.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. lived alone in his Montérégie apartment.
The prostate cancer that was destroying him had given him a two-year break.
“I had been given five years to live, but I have been like this for seven years,” he says, lying in his bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care centre in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
“But it’s always a shock, we can’t be prepared for this,” he continues.
The disease has wreaked havoc on him: a huge weakness that prevents him from going to the bathroom alone and even eating alone.
Sitting in front of an appetizing lunch, he accepts resigned to being helped to eat.
Brave, he even smiles, talks to strangers who devote attention to him, bring him medicine and offer him a bath.
The Courage of Ordinary Death.
“My biggest wish is that my diarrhea is cured, it’s humiliating,” she confesses.
A few hours later, the team found a remedy for that evil.
“Over the course of our lives we learn that a man pees on his feet,” says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois centre.
Going back to childhood, for some people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
“That depends on the person’s ability to accept that regression,” he says.
Because, in the opinion of most people who work in palliative care, the great moments take place at the very heart of that regression.
All patients who enter the Victor-Gadbois palliative care center have cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
In that state, the team of doctors and nurses around them no longer offer “cure” care.
Ms. A.’s biggest fear, 89, is dying “consciously and drowning.”
But the disease has made him discover his children.
“I have good kids,” he adds.
“I have no desires left in this life,” she says, before accepting a mask to help her breathe.
In the next few days, he expects a final visit from his son who lives in Italy.
Victor-Gadbois offers, with a group of volunteers, body care and food aid.
They are palliative care that is given to them when nothing else can be done.
To help make your death more comfortable.
In Quebec, we have one palliative care bed for every 11,700 inhabitants.
It is very little, since we know that we will all end up dying one day.
Here, life continues in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors at the center.
Whether at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is offered mouthwashes with brandy or Pepsi, according to the lawsuit.
Diabetics are no longer in control of their sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer, who died in the course of the night.
This morning, his son ran out of beer at the deceased's feet.
“We help patients and their loved ones alike,” says Nathalie Savard, director of care.
In the center Victor-Gadbois the days pass without ever being the same.
Alongside a 94-year-old man enjoying his last family reunion in the yard, well placed between his pillows while everyone drinks to his health, a 36-year-old man tragically dies, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two children, after having tried everything to survive.
“For the past six months, there have always been three to five beds occupied by people under the age of 45 who have cancer,” says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of the patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadboisarrivent center come from home and 47% from the hospital.
Access to palliative care
Seventy-seven per cent of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care designed to alleviate suffering when a patient reaches the terminal stage of his or her life, whether at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois center and the home palliative care society of Grand Montréal, specialize almost exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this great relative lack of health care in Quebec that makes many doctors specializing in palliative care fear the adoption of a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto signed by eminences of palliative care, such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec’s health care system is not competent enough to ensure that anyone is entitled to quality palliative care before euthanasia is accepted.
"Recently," he relates, "I have seen a patient spend 14 days in the ER suffering great pains without having done what was necessary to relieve her.
I fear that patients want to die just because they don’t get proper care.”
And in parallel, many oncologists are stubborn with their patients until the last day, despite the worst prognoses.
Helene Richard’s hopes of survival were already low when she left a grueling chemotherapy treatment.
“When I told my oncologist that I wanted to stop the treatment, she told me that she was very sorry that she wanted to stop fighting,” she says.
"However, she had told me there was nothing else to do!"
There is no almighty care.
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who request to die thank their caregivers for not attending to their demands once their pain has been relieved thanks to a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful when it comes to treating pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of home palliative care in Grand Montréal, patients do not respond to pain treatments in 8% of cases.
At the end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which serves to sleep the patient until the moment of his death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can’t pretend that we don’t understand that part of suffering.
Increasingly, the disease not relieved will have the possibility of having that palliative sedation.
The sick who are not relieved say the same thing: "I want to die."
But that does not necessarily mean “I want euthanasia”, but “I want to be relieved”.
