A Constitution with forceps in Egypt
It is a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever as to the constitutional declaration, which provisionally grants it full powers, he decided to play the whole for the whole.
It caught everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when it announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Only a week ago, the Head of State had given the Assembly two more months to complete its work.
And for almost two years Egypt has been using a provisional text, several times modified, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial scramble.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president perseveres in his "autocratic delusion" and continues to "betray his word" and "treat the right."
On the part of his supporters, he said it was a measure to end the institutional and political crisis faster and accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be held in the next 15 days.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to give up their project of explaining the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversy is wreaking havoc across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in his favor, as he claimed in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Considering that this appeal has been voted on very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "either they vote on my text or I retain full powers", powers that are supposed to come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in that strange atmosphere that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, Islamist in their vast majority, voted on the text yesterday.
Most of the Liberals did not attend the call.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they felt they could not assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 substitute members were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
As expected, the articles voted unanimously.
Commentators are amused, on the other hand, by the fact that one of the few discrepancies of the day was expressed practically at the time of prayer, so much so that several members of the committee came to think that the clock of the Constituent Assembly was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday afternoon, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, the object of all considerations, remains ultimately identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, which stipulated that "the principles of Sharia constitute the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental demand, hoped that "principles" could be replaced by "norms", which would have allowed a stricter application.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
The liberals call it hypocrisy and consider it nothing more than an advertising gimmick.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer in particular to article 220, which confers on Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular for anyone who has to confirm its compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because “people called upon to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we glimpse the premises of a theocracy."
The fears of the liberals are further compounded by the fact that the next rector of the university would be far less moderate than the current rector.
“For now, there is no concrete religious implication.
With this Constitution we are within the framework of the civil status.
The majority of the jurists who have worked on this text are not ulemas but university students, some of them trained in the French system," explains Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that there may be some ambiguity around article 220, since the terms used mimic the religious vocabulary.
"We are referring specifically to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence].
And the question that might arise in the future would be to what extent civil judges are competent to rule above all this.”
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday has received many criticisms that refer to the extended powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood will claim that they are few compared to those they were during the previous regime.
Another point of conflict: the powers conferred on the army.
According to the wishes of the military, the revision of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Neither will the prosecution of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as called for by human rights associations.
They also expressed their concerns about the text, which they consider to be liberticidal.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and, from now on, insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially that of the press.
In addition, no article emphasizes the protection of women, Human Rights Watch’s Heba Morayef underlines.
According to her, the only positive thing had been the prohibition of torture in accordance with article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous Constitution.
Although the Egyptian president was due to appear on television last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state demonstrated on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are waiting for the holy land, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land combines the majesty of biblical truths with modern comfort and pristine nature.
"AIF" identified the five most important reasons why you should visit Israel.
Reverence in the Holy Land
It is worth visiting the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is believed that anyone who enters this “baptismal stack” will receive divine grace.
And Galilee, the place of Jesus’ miracles: the conversion of water into wine at the wedding, walking on the waters, the appeasement of the storm and the filling of nets.
In this same place, Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
But most of the holy places are in Jerusalem.
Here believers travel the Via Crucis or the Way of the Cross of Jesus (in Latin "Vía Dolorosa").
It begins in the Fortress of Anthony, the Praetorium, where the trial took place, and continues through the streets of the Old City, goes to the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha, the place of the Crucifixion, to the Stone of the Anointing and the place of the burial of Jesus.
In this same place is also the symbolic Christian Navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of humanity.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem, built in the place where, according to a Christian legend, there was a tree that was made the cross for the crucifixion of Jesus.
In Jerusalem is also the holiest place for the Jews, the Western Wall; the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
As is tradition, people of different religions leave here notes with their wishes, which will then become a reality.
Making a Vertical Journey
The ruins of the Masada Fortress were what remained of a secret shelter from enemies, which Herod the Great had built in 25 BC for his family.
They are located on the mountain cliffs at a height of 450 m above sea level.
And to get there by their own means, can only those who engage in climbing.
The others can reach this historic summit on the funicular.
And in the north of the country at an altitude of 1600-2040 m is the famous ski resort Hermon, where in the winter months there is a large influx of tourists.
Up there, from the foot of the hill bus services are offered.
The total length of the ski slopes is 45 km.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods supposedly lived on top of the mountain.
Visiting Unique Museums
There are about 300 museums in the country.
In one trip you won’t be able to visit them all.
But it is worth visiting at least five of them, the most interesting ones.
Among them is the Israel Museum, located near the Knesset (Israeli Parliament).
It preserves the ancient Dead Sea Scrolls or Qumran Scrolls, discovered in the caves of the Judean desert, and about 500,000 archaeological and anthropological pieces.
It is worth visiting the Museum of Art in Tel Aviv.
In his exhibition of paintings he has canvases of Impressionists and Expressionists such as Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall or Picasso.
In Acre you can visit the museum-bath Al Basha, which are some rooms of ancient Turkish baths with models of visitors and bathers of that time.
In Caesarea it is worth visiting the exclusive private Ralli museum, where you can admire the sculptures of Rodin and Dalí.
There are no tour guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free, and donations are categorically not accepted.
The fifth, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, features one of the most dramatic pages in history.
The most tragic section is the Children’s Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children killed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter it and find yourself in absolute darkness.
The stars are shining.
And the names of the Jewish children ring and the names of the countries in which they lost their lives.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health
The three main tourist areas of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of them there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanographic museums.
It is curious that in the Red Sea they bathe even in the winter months, since the water temperature does not drop below 21 degrees and the air warms up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and they bathe there all year round.
By the way, this sea, the most extraordinary in the world, is at the lowest point on the planet: 417 m below sea level.
The blue waters there are a brine that easily hold even those who cannot swim.
The surrounding landscapes are truly beautiful.
People come here to take courses of treatment with salt water, brine and healing muds and strengthen their health in cases of dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to put their broken nerves in order.
Touching the Mysteries of Antiquity
They are preserved in the old part of Tel Aviv, the citadel of Jaffa, on the Mediterranean coast.
It passed the famous maritime route that united Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and Perseus rescued the beautiful Andromeda with whom, in this same place, he led a long and happy life.
Tourists love to stroll through the narrow streets that bear the names of the signs of the Zodiac.
They say that if you touch the walls on the street of your "same" symbol, fortune will be favorable to you.
In Jaffa you can find newlywed couples who come from all over Israel, and even from other countries to photograph themselves.
And in Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theater, "take" the fortress of the crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman procurators, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for night concerts and opera performances.
Tourists remember
If you travel to Israel, don’t worry if your English leaves much to be desired: in this country about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
The money for this trip is not recommended to be carried in euros, but in dollars, which can be easily exchanged for shekels (currently $1-3,8 shekels).
Urban transport consists mainly of buses, but in Jerusalem there are fast trams and in Haifa there is the only metro line in the country, consisting of six stations and connecting the Lower City with the Upper City.
Actually, it's from an underground funicular.
Traveling in any type of public transport costs 6 shekels and for this price you can travel by transfer for 1.5 hours.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated on Saturdays.
From Friday night to Saturday night, markets and shops close and public transport interrupts their work.
On Sunday morning, a new work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, unflaked fish and dishes in which milk and meat are combined.
There is a wide selection of dishes based on beef and lamb, soups and desserts prepared with coconut milk, the traditional Hebrew cream called hummus, great variety of sauces, the phalafel, which are ground chickpea balls, fruits and vegetables.
In the streets of Israeli cities you don’t see stray dogs.
Instead, there are a lot of well-fed cats that "walk to their liking" imposingly.
At night you can see them sleeping even on the roofs of parked cars.
Snorers love busy places and do not reject treats.
Renting a car, depending on the brand, will cost from $37 (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80) per day.
In addition to insurance, it goes out for $ 15 a day.
And renting a bike will cost you 15 shekels a day.
Museum tickets cost an average of 30 shekels.
Israel in numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
The majority of those who came to tour the country and rest were citizens of the US, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, the United Kingdom and Ukraine.
The Promised Land, from January to October 2012, was visited by 118,800 Ukrainian tourists, a figure that exceeds by 51% the same rate of 2010, before the cancellation of the visa regime on February 9, 2011.
"The Great and Powerful" will take you to Moscow: immigrants save for the language
While deputies and human rights defenders discuss the consequences of the law on compulsory examination, scammers have already appeared in the country who trade in "false" certificates
Every year, 13 million immigrant workers arrive in Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most are citizens of Central Asian countries: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to make money to help their families who have stayed home.
As of December 1, a law comes into force, according to which every work immigrant must take an exam to check their knowledge of the Russian language.
For now, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the service provision sector, community service institutions, domestic services and retail trade.
However, in time, as promised by the Federal Immigration Service, exams will become mandatory for all immigrants.
Moreover, it will not be enough to pass the examination of the language, but also that of Russian history and the foundations of legislation.
Knowledge of the language must be confirmed even to receive and renew the work permit.
The exception is citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Persons who obtained their education certificates and diplomas before the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991 will not be subject to this law.
Utility, Fatality and Defense of Rights
The network of examination centres will operate under the auspices of the Pushkin Russian Language Institute, Peoples ' Friendship University, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to take part in the tests in all cities, and more than 160 such centers are currently open in Russia.
The initiative on the introduction of the examination was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Immigration Service.
But rights defenders, long before the law came into force, managed to ask the press this question many times: And what will this actually bring?
What changes will the compulsory knowledge of the language bring, both for Russians and for immigrants themselves?
First, replies the representatives of the Immigration Service, this will allow to reduce the number of people who suffer "working slavery".
Many people talk today about defending the rights of labour immigrants, explains Victor Sebelev, head of the representation of the Russian Federal Immigration Service in Tajikistan.
The defense of your rights must be initiated before your departure.
Only an organized selection system will solve the problem of immigrant workers in 90% of cases.
The problems are faced by immigrants with no profession, no education, those who do not know the language and do not pass medical check-ups.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev says, the future immigrant will be condemned to find unscrupulous people who, under the pretext of helping, sneak a "paid trip" to a creepy, narrow covacha, where he and dozens of others like him are consumed for months without food or documents, working 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive countless complaints from our immigrants.
"In their homeland they are promised one thing, but when they arrive they are deceived, they are deprived of their passports, they are not paid the promised wages," said Tolib Sharipov, head of the Tajik Immigration Service's Labour Immigration Directorate.
Don't get mad, little boss!
However, in the meantime many citizens of the Central Asian republics who wish to work in Russia recognize that they not only do not know the language of the country they intend to go to, but also write with difficulty in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault but their own misfortune: few Turkmen, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to receive normal primary education.
This is because their families even have nothing to feed the children, not to mention dress them, shoes and buy what they need for school.
As they reach adolescence, these boys venture to work at the first opportunity.
It’s hard, if you don’t know the language, they recognize it.
"One feels humiliated and inferior."
However, as far as the language law is concerned, rights advocates point to an important point.
The exams will be conducted only for those immigrants whose status is legal.
If they do not have that status, there will be no exam and consequently no official work.
Meanwhile, most immigrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or forbidden passage to strangers"
Many visitors claim that receiving official status in our country is not so easy.
The cause lies in the bureaucratic obstacles and difficulties of the language itself.
In addition, legalization costs money: from twelve thousand to sixteen thousand rubles.
However, a false inscription can be made quickly and for only one thousand five hundred rubles.
Employees of the Russian police know that we usually carry false documents, we are not registered and extortion cases appear.
"We are asked 100 or 200 rubles for cigarettes or tea," Tajik citizen Umed Hushkadamov told reporters.
"Come on, don't be stubborn, buy a painting"
On the first day of the entry into force of the language law, it was revealed that not only immigrant registration documents can be false.
Several “false” certificates of knowledge of the language have already been seized by officials of the Federal Immigration Service.
The counterfeit documents had been printed on standard color printers.
Of course, they came into the hands of the new owners not as a gift: each immigrant, wanting to facilitate the task of passing the tests, paid for the document seven thousand rubles.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official examination procedure, which will cost the immigrant worker three thousand rubles.
The main task for the near future is to protect the system against corruption so that “diplomas” cannot be bought, government officials and rights defenders converge.
So far, the authorities can promise immigrant workers who could not pass the exam the first time more time to study the basic course of the language.
In addition, immigrants who do not speak Russian will be offered jobs that do not require active communication with people.
The Ministry of the Interior does not take drastic measures against the illegal arms trade
The percentage of crimes committed with registered weapons is quite small
The Ministry of the Interior proposes to apply the law with greater rigidity in relation to the owners of weapons for civil use.
This is the government’s reaction to the recent incidents: Tightening shots during wedding celebrations in which luckily there were no casualties, and the massacre initiated by Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov, in which Tighten seven people lost their lives.
Police want to ban the use and possession of traumatic weapons in public places and raise the minimum age for obtaining a license to carry weapons from 18 years to 21 years.
