As for the offices, such as the NK<0xC3><0x9A>, there is the Bundesrechnungshof (Federal Court of Auditors), with an organization similar to ours, with a school as well, the only thing is that in its case it is structured in a somewhat different way, but in principle both offices evolve in parallel.
The powers are also to some extent analogous, however, while Germany has a federal organization, the courts of account are even at this level. In this respect it differs slightly from our system.
The Federal Court of Auditors (BRH) can only control federal money, which here we call state funds.
Public funds, which are administered by the regions and municipalities, there, in Germany, are controlled by the Federal Court of Auditors.
As for local legislation, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would not like to make a comparison without specific data, but Germany is still a model in some respects, but it is not possible to specify exactly what is best.
Could it be better, for example, in terms of the quality of inspectors?
Surely not, but, I repeat, I don’t like to make such comparisons.
It is necessary to say that even those countries that we take as a model must face a large number of problems.
If it weren't, they wouldn't benefit from collaborating with our office, would they?
As regards the legislation of our country, what did the amendment of the law on public procurement mean to your Office?
Given that the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been manifested in the control proceedings.
As we carry out ex-post checks, we need to have a certain amount of delay.
For now, it is observed in the process of preparing the future controls: we have started a new tool of "detection of non-economic risks", through which we have passed almost 14,000 public tenders, which have been analyzed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, since the limits are modified, the conditions of some types of the selection process are rectified and the like.
Do you consider the passage of this law to be beneficial or rather a mess for the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is surely a step in the right direction and I hope it is.
The problem that may arise is that the regulation "hardens" and that it is impossible to comply with it.
Already with the previous regulations, the controlled persons were linked to the contractor (for example, in the case of the regional operational programmes of the regional council), and every non-compliance with the law on public procurement meant a violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense then to harden the law in this way?
I don't think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack it or take advantage of it and not punish those who make a formal ruling, which has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only create greater bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We will see where this path leads us.
The Prime Minister has recently stated that the SDG would not disturb entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called <0xC5><0xA1>varc system, with reference to the fact that it is autonomous only on paper. What does this mean?
Is the "<0xC5><0xA1>varc" system prohibited or allowed?
The law must be regulated in some way and, if it prohibits anything, then even the prime minister of the government cannot prevent the action of the Office that has an obligation to carry out such controls and demand obligations.
He can say, "We change the law and allow it," but he can't say we're going to do anything.
In the law on public procurement, the rules are quite strict as to how to act formally. And that is how it should be to protect public competition.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic that the candidate with the best offer is excluded for not meeting formal requirements.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct. This is, in my opinion, what we lack.
