Poland and the cosmos.
At the meeting of ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency held last week, Poland was accepted as the twelfth member of ESA. It is the second ESA member country of the former Eastern European bloc, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008.
Poland began an intense collaboration with ESA in 1994 and during the following years participated in the commissioning of the agency’s projects.
However, Poland’s path to the cosmos began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already engaged in spaceflight before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, the lecture of A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld at the astronomical observatory in Warsaw in which, on December 6, 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneering study "Introduction to cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the attendees indifferent and, years later, <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld recalled that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch awards in France for his "Introduction to cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a series of books dedicated to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, was known around the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when he named one of the craters on the moon's hidden face.
Already in 1925 a dresin was built in Poland that was to be provided with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, it is unknown who was the author of the proposal and the details of the project are not known.
It is unclear whether the rocket was to be used for the start of the dresin or for braking.
The information about this dresine is limited to the collection in the press of the time.
In 1933, Polish artillery began to focus on missiles.
The research was funded by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustawem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the preserved material, it becomes clear that the investigation reached the stage of practical testing.
However, with the arrival of German troops, the investigation was halted.
In 1937 appeared in the specialized press the prototype of a photoelectric hunting missile designed by the engineer Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski and the following year was published the study "Rakieta - torpedo powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza", by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki.
Both projects were intended for military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all projects of missile techniques for military use and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the beginning of the war.
Other studies dedicated to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The November 1954 issue of the journal Problemy refers for the first time to society with four very extensive articles dedicated to astronautics.
In one of them, Prof. M. Subotowicze proposed the creation of a society dedicated to cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with prospects for the future.
From the beginning of 1956 the Polish Society of Astronautics (PTA) aspired to become part of the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951) and in the autumn of that same year the PTA became a full member.
The following year the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became the vice-president of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA was significantly involved in the development of the RM probe rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which was a success and became the first Polish rocket in which scientific research was carried out.
The first RM-1 type was completed in 1957 and first launched on October 10, 1958.
The rocket had an apogee of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm in length and did not reach 5 kg in weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed and in the summer of 1959 aerial tests of the two-stage RM-2 rockets began in the B<0xC5><0x82><0xC4><0x99>dów desert.
The rocket measured 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of rocket in development was to be the subject of real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was to have a peak of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the wind from height.
In 1962, however, work was suspended.
The successor of the first rockets of the RM type was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during the years 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed from each other by the space available for scientific apparatus.
In the Meteor-1A rocket the space available for the volume was 0.4 liters, in the Meteor-1B 0.34 liters and in the Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The maximum apogee in the three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968 the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, whose first aerial tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a useful weight of 10 kg up to 60 km in height.
Later the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also necessary to mention the entry of Poland into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in the year 1960 and the formation of the national committee of COSPAR two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos program, Poland joined cosmic space research on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimír Remek.
The suspension of the social work law is not the solution.
Last week the constitutional court suspended the social labor law.
The resolution sparked a heated discussion in society.
It will certainly be interesting to examine the existing problem from a broader point of view.
Liberal economic systems in the EU, as in the globalised world, are based on the principle of greater economic competition and less regulation.
Consequently, this means that the different economic forms and national economic systems are in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause lies in the principle of free trade and the free and unlimited movement of private capital, together with unbridled financial speculation.
The effect of large differences in labour cost (wages) produces economic tensions.
Under this concept it is necessary to understand the situation in which the manufacturer, by importing cheap goods, tries to shorten distances and to do so "causes a drop" in the price of the competitor with the aim of taking over the majority of the market and, in this way, increase its profit margin.
On a large scale, for most entrepreneurs, it means moving production abroad, buying there cheaper or disappearing, and the result is high unemployment in those countries where the price of labour, compared to other economies, is higher.
Because private capital has no social responsibility and is therefore not responsible for the unemployment that this phenomenon generates, the social expenditure of the state necessarily grows.
All this situation promotes the total disinterest of the entrepreneurs in paying taxes and compensating for the economic and social damages that they have caused in their eagerness to obtain profits.
The situation is so universally known that it is not necessary to submit specific statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create situations, in certain economies, in which the governments of those countries are forced to compete with the aim of artificially reducing the social level of the population itself and, in this way, attracting foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments make private capital available to their own population without regard to social decline.
This is especially evident in changes to existing laws.
The aim is to force the population to accept the dictate of private capital, especially with regard to wages.
This takes place, on the one hand, through the system of economic obligation in the case of long-term unemployment; on the other hand, through the restricted right of employees as regards labour rights.
The result is growing poverty along with increasing gaps between the poor and the rich.
For a number of years, there have been food delivery points in Germany for poor people who cannot support themselves with their own work.
The number of people receiving this type of aid is already at one million.
In the context of the increasing competitiveness of the German economy, a fairly frequent case occurs: people employed at such a low wage that the state must pay the rest to reach the minimum essential to survive.
A scandal of this kind related to the situation of auxiliary employees of the German federal parliament was made public.
The savings measures of practically all the southern EU states lead, without a doubt, to the same situation: people, pressured by an abysmal decline in their social level, are forced to emigrate as in the 19th century or to live with a poor salary at the edge of society, in the hope that one day private investor capital will arrive in the country.
Is it necessary to ask where it comes from?
In the case of other EU countries, then poverty passes from one country to another or never arrives, since Chinese, Indians, Brazilians, Turks, Moroccans, Egyptians or Africans continue to work for a tiny part of a European wage.
This also affects all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media affirm to the full that the state should not bring capital to the economy, that directing the economy leads to its failure.
Private capital defends with fingernails and teeth the thesis that the state should not intervene in the economy by meddling in control.
Then it is necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence with its egoism the political march and, therefore, the whole state.
In this case, the answer is clearly affirmative.
The proof is the existence of lobbies, in practice very powerful and ubiquitous, in all states.
The result is a desperate situation that manifests itself in the realm of corruption, in mutual favors, in legislation that is practically reprehensible everywhere but not punishable.
In Germany, the situation is as follows: State ministries, in the absence of financial means, commission the drafting of bills to private legal firms, which are often linked to industry.
Such bills are then passed in the Bundestag, the German parliament.
In this way, all power emanates not from the people, as announced in the constitutions of Western democracies, but from the strong financial groups that represent their own interests.
It is obvious that democracies with a liberal orientation are quickly in a situation such as that described by Appianos in his work The Crisis of the Roman Republic in the Time of Caesar and Pompeii: "The state had been disintegrating for some time and the administrations occupied themselves by force."
In exchange for bribes, favors obtained illegitimately and help to finance stones or swords.
The bribery and corruption spread without any hindrance and the people went to the polls with the vote beaten beforehand"... "there were no people of character who aspired to a post in the administration, so once, because of this disorganization, the state was eight months without consuls"... "It began to be spoken in serious to the App" to the autistic power that the only remedy for such a serious situation was the aut man.
The conclusion, as in antiquity, is that today’s society is based on disregarded preferences of individual benefit without regard to common interests.
Private capital is not, in its essence, capable of understanding and claiming the benefits of the whole society.
The result is the same as then, an unprecedented decline of the elite, with no effort being made to reform it in depth.
The causes of the rise of fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the unbridled liberalization of economic systems in the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.
With respect to the current situation, it is possible to consider the disappearance of these systems in favour of a liberal democracy, as a definite pause, pending the next coup.
The truly devastating fact is that today’s elite completely ignore the loss of hundreds of thousands of lives, the social and humanitarian catastrophes we have witnessed, as well as the crimes against humanity as we know them in ancient and recent history.
Suspension of the public procurement law is not the solution; at least not in the long run.
Under pressure from economic competition, both internationally and within the EU, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue looking for other ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The solution passes through concrete socio-political reforms, which strengthen both the participation of state capital and the influence of citizens in government and weaken the position of monopoly of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
