Argo Movie: If It Gets Raw, Call Hollywood
In November 1979 a group of Islamist student protesters occupied the American embassy in Tehran and took 52 graduates as hostages.
His release was to be in exchange for dethroned Shah Mohamed Reza Pahlevi, who after the revolution fled to the United States, a country that had sponsored his regime for decades.
For the American administration the situation did not offer any positive perspective: throwing the shah overboard could not afford it, since, if it did, it endangered the confidence of its allies in other countries.
But the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution had led to the constitution of the theocratic regime, was out of reach.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which subsequently intensified further with the failed attempt to free the hostages by force.
The detained diplomats were released 444 days after the Algerian government’s negotiating intervention.
In the US, his fate caused a wave of solidarity and animosity against Iran.
Failure in Iran contributed decisively to Jimmy Carter’s defeat of Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film "Argo" by director and actor Ben Affleck themes an episode of this story, which was a small success for America.
Shortly before occupying the embassy, six employees escaped from the building.
After a complicated journey, they ended up in the residence of the Canadian embassy.
CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, to help a cover story an extravagant point: they came out with Canadian passports, as members of the film team examining the location in the country for the filming of a sci-fi blockbuster.
Combination of Genders
The plan that "exfiltration" expert Toni Mendez mapped out required Hollywood's collaboration.
To make the lie seem true, the film project was written about in specialized magazines, press conferences were organized, the fictional production society even had a real office.
The details about the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film has been made from the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck’s film is a unique combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller; on the other, a so-called "caper movie", the story of an episode that went well, a hoax (an example can be the Ocean's Eleven series).
The film combines moods. We find on the one hand well-documented sequences of Tehran. In the sequence of credits are shown emblematic photographs of the time of the events, which were captured in the same way in the film; there are not many differences in this regard.
On the other hand, typical scenes of Hollywood a little lighter, marked by irony and a slight exaggeration.
And besides, scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions: men in suits analyzing the situation at the negotiating table, in the corridors of the office, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in an excellent way.
The actor, who had been mocked, has become a respectable director and his way of acting has ceased to be the target of ironic comments.
Argo is his third feature film, after "Bye-bye little, Good-bye" (2007) and the thriller "The Town. City of Thieves" (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck’s first film in which the action does not take place in the city of Boston, where he was raised.
Also, the sensitivity of capturing the atmosphere of the place was a feature that placed the directors of old films above Hollywood standards.
And Affleck demonstrates it in Argo, where Tehran is “wheeling” in Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, in the reconstruction of the true events. The introductory sequence of the taking of the embassy is impressive for its synoptic capacity that, at the same time, transmits the emotion of the bewilderment and the lack of foresight that arises when, somewhere, the story takes a step forward.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect in the fictional scenes (the imposter team at the Tehran bazaar).
Too much action in too many places
The director had to accept the fact that a story told doesn’t offer much in the cinematic sense of the most intriguing scenes.
Sometimes it adds something to the reality: everything doesn’t turn out so elegantly here (the scene of the crisis at Tehran’s airport, the diversion of a call to America and the rampant search for its trail turns into madness).
Argo’s weakness is the out of control that arises from the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman have a very funny role as Hollywood collaborators, although their characters deserved more space and are not, much less, the only ones in this film.
For these reasons, Affleck’s film loses a bit of dramatic plot, but it is a film that can be followed with a moderate interest, value its realization and the retro style of a thriller that evokes the 70s.
But if it collapses, it will be difficult.
As an evocation of a true story and as proof of how exaggerated the notions of the omnipresence and omniscience of the secret services can be, it is enough.
