Prosecutors sought to show Friday that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of confidential information in U.S. history, missed multiple opportunities to report the ill-treatment he now alleges he suffered while in military detention.
During the prosecution’s interrogation of Manning at a pretrial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Chief Prosecutor Ashden Fein stated that records of weekly visits by unit officers that Manning received during nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, do not show any complaints about the treatment he was receiving.
The interrogation, which took place during a hearing following the defence ' s request that the case be dismissed given that his imprisonment had been harsh and that this had already entailed sufficient punishment, came a day after Manning testified that he had thought of committing suicide while in detention.
