WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of the information.
In Friday’s hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms officers filled out after visits to Manning during his arrest at the Quantico military prison, where he was held in maximum confinement from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers would have asked Manning questions and written down his answers.
When Fein asked about the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that he had described the treatment given to him by the caretakers as "excellent" and the treatment received at the facility in general as "very professional."
The forms show no allegations of ill-treatment, even though officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he was receiving, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern about certain issues and that the officers visiting him had spoken about those issues and had indicated that they would be addressed, but that they had not recorded those issues in the record.
“They wrote ‘no incidents’ (after talking about problems) but that doesn’t necessarily mean I wouldn’t have mentioned any problems,” Manning said.
The judge, Army Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why she had not reported the treatment she was receiving during the January 2011 meeting with a board tasked with examining suicide intentions that she had expressed on a form months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during that meeting was to get the reduction of the "injury prevention" regime under which he was.
The military said it had put him under that restrictive regime, which is one degree below surveillance for possible suicide, to ensure his protection and the safety of others.
“I wanted the staff to know that I was okay and (wanted) to stop being under injury prevention ... so I could enjoy what, from my point of view, is a better quality of life,” Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison at the Marine Corps base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered committing suicide in Kuwait and had once lost consciousness due to the heat.
He said that the fact that he was not allowed to know what was happening to him or what was happening in the outside world was very distressing.
"My world was reduced only to Camp Arafjon, to that cage," Manning said Thursday.
