Manning claimed that, once moved to Quantico, he spent most of his days in a small cell, at least for 21 hours and often for 23 hours, unaccompanied.
Manning said he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, some clothes and his glasses.
He explained that he tried to move all the time, as it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
Manning said he always had a light coming from outside pointing at his eyes while he was sleeping.
He said that if the janitors could not see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him to turn around again.
Manning’s lawyer filed a formal complaint in January 2011 about Manning’s treatment.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth Military Prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation she had made in Thursday’s statement that, after being forced to sleep naked in his Quantico cell one night, he was forced to stand naked in front of caretakers and other prisoners during a morning count.
Manning had testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover himself with a blanket during the count.
During the judge’s interrogation on Friday, Manning said she inferred from the order given to her by the janitor that she should drop the blanket she might have covered herself with, but acknowledged that no one had ordered her to drop it.
Manning testified Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning said he had told the officer that he could have used the elastic in his underwear or flip-flops to self-injure himself but had not.
Manning testified that his underwear, flip-flops and glasses had been removed from his cell that night.
Her lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account the experiences she went through during her time in prison and drastically reduce her sentence in case he is convicted in court, which is scheduled to begin early next year.
The defense said it plans to have Manning plead guilty to misdemeanor offences and defend other charges deemed too extreme.
