Australia’s pioneering generic tobacco and packaging law comes into force, replacing brand logos and colors with an olive-green off wrapper, frightening images of diseased body parts and depictions of children and babies who are sick because they are the children of parents who smoke.
With the exception of the various images and health warnings, the only difference between the boxes, mandatory since Saturday, are the names of the brands, all printed in a small typeface.
This is the world’s strictest regime for tobacco packaging.
The federal government of Australia claims that the goal is to deter young people from smoking by removing the traits that make this habit glamorous.
Trust studies that show that if a person hasn’t started smoking before the age of 26, there’s a 99% chance they’ll never do it.
"You can see that children, even from a very young age, understand the message that the tobacco company is trying to sell through its brand," said federal health minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that showed, for example, how girls linked the logo of a crown to the idea of being a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and these changes will not affect the profits of multinationals much, other countries are considering similar measures.
