Petronella Wyatt: 'I was harassed until I got kicked out of Oxford for being a Tory'
Students are not attacked for their views only now
I don’t remember any time in my life where I haven’t been dreaming of getting a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother had been at what I thought was the best place in the world to learn, a contemporary Greek symposium that fostered the two pillars of civilization: free thinking and tolerance.
However, within two weeks of taking up my place at Worcester College in the late 1980s to pursue a career in History, I had already packed my bags, which triggered the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed and started to cry.
My friends were bewildered.
The Evening Standard newspaper claimed that I had given up because I did not tolerate some college classmates having sex in the next room.
The writer A. N. Wilson announced jokingly that I had left because I was forced to drink in chapped cups.
The truth was less fun.
I ran away from there.
Yes, I fled, because I had been subjected to systematic harassment and intimidation.
Not because of my extravagant name, or the fact that I came from a private school.
I was harassed for a single reason, which in the cradle of the supposed illustration was somewhat intolerant and barbaric: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a prominent adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I supported the Conservative Party.
You may wonder what that comes to now.
Well, several reports indicate that a new generation of middle-right students is suffering similar persecution.
The institutionalized and growing hatred of Conservative Party students is such in Oxford that last week a group of them claimed the same level of equal rights as homosexuals, the disabled and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of Corpus Christi College's JCR say they are "often seriously sidelined, personally attacked and treated as ungrateful people" for their political ideas.
They want to create a position on their college’s Equal Opportunity Committee to make sure they can express their opinions freely.
His situation was not favored by a recent BBC2 documentary called "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right" about student politics and which presented the Tories as eccentrics and neo-Nazis.
It showed graduate student Joe Cooke, former president of the Conservative Party Association of the University of Oxford (OUCA), in a Rolls-Royce, wearing a silver suit and a cane with a silver handle.
At other universities, conservative students say they are treated as "Turkish heads" by introducing higher tuition fees.
Luke Black, a 20-year-old vice president of the Conservative Party Association at the University of Nottingham, said in a Sunday newspaper that “there is a growing trend of leftists in universities.
“People assume we’re like the Bullingdon Club without even knowing each other.”
Samuel Roberts, a 21-year-old history student at Corpus Christi who filed the motion for greater protection, says this environment is “uncomfortable,” while Stephanie Cherill, a 19-year-old president-elect of the OUCA, says JCR members’ attitude toward people who are center-right has worsened.
“This poses a threat to the intellectual debate environment, as well as to the well-being of members,” he says.
During my first few weeks at Oxford I was lonelier than one.
I entered college in September 1986, I was a terribly shy 18-year-old girl.
The hatred of the Conservative Party was at its highest.
The year before, the university had voted to deny former student Margaret Thatcher an honoris causa degree following cuts in funding for higher education.
The atmosphere would have made any Stalinist shudder with awe.
Already during the first days of the welcome week for new university students, when new students meet and meet professors, I received a sample of the bitterness that awaited me.
I discovered that the professors not only turned a blind eye to the mockery of conservative university students, but also participated in it willingly.
The policy of the miners’ strike, privatization and government opposition to apartheid sanctions in South Africa reached the wooden halls of the seminary.
The first I attended had to be translated into English French texts of the eighteenth century and I was not prepared for what came next.
"Miss Wyatt," said Professor Harry Pitt (already deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
Not a single one.
Pitt, a short man with a face that looked like cake dough, knew well how to expel bad bile.
“Do Thatcherists refuse to learn French, or are they just silly?” he asked.
The other students laughed.
My eyes were burning with the tears I was trying to contain.
“I suggest you go to French classes in your spare time, as long as you’re not too busy meeting people,” Pitt grunted.
I returned to my room like a soul in grief.
That night I sat alone at dinner time at the university; then I felt a slight slap on my back.
He was a second-year English student named James who introduced himself as a member of the OUCA.
“I know who you are,” he said kindly.
“I’m afraid that’s how it goes.
They mess with anyone who's suspected of being Tory.
It's very complicated for me, but they know your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it'll be even worse for you.
Many newly arrived Tories appear to be Labour.”
Later, in a local pub, I cowardly tried to hide.
I insisted that I did not agree with everything that Mrs Thatcher said.
That trick proved useless.
A first-year student of Philosophy, Politics and Economics who, paradoxically, had studied at Eton, said: "You are the daughter of a fascist pig.
You are contaminated.”
Other students adopted that song.
I became the dirty pervert.
“How do the Tories have sex?” one asked.
"They beat each other up, don't they?"
I felt the same way homosexuals should have felt before the liberal law of the 1960s.
Could he ever lead a normal life in Oxford?
Would I be forced to hang out with people who thought like me only after dark?
Should I become a Labourist and suppress my natural tendencies?
The three years that awaited me were presented as a purgatory of ostracism and isolation.
The only openly Tory professor was Norman Stone, a Professor of Contemporary History assigned to my college.
They hated him for being not only the Conservative Party, but also Thatcher’s foreign policy adviser and one of the people who wrote her speeches.
I was barely there.
He detested the place because he considered it provincial and insignificant and because of its adherence to the Marxist-determinist view of history.
In 1997 he accepted a chair at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
“You’re not going to be happy here,” he said.
I started commuting daily from Oxford to my parents’ home in London, finding refuge in my more open-minded metropolitan family and friends.
I told my father I hated Oxford and why.
He didn't believe me.
When he studied there in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
“But it’s the best place in the world,” he said sadly.
“They would never do that, not there among my dear dream needles.
Even my communist friends always had an impeccable attitude.”
His painful eyes began to cloud.
"Give him another chance.
I'm sure they did it just for fun.
It would break my heart if you let me.”
Exhausted from so many trips to London, my emotional stamina was deteriorating.
A friend of mine, who also supported the Conservative Party, had succumbed to pressure and renounced his creed.
The following week, during a seminar in which another professor of history had implied, quite seriously, that I was an “enemy of the people,” I decided to do the same.
Red with shame on the inside, I admitted that my parents had “brainwashed” me and called them “stupid old men.”
The truce lasted a short time.
It was my father who put the last nail in the coffin of my university career at Oxford.
At that time my father wrote two columns a week in Murdoch’s press.
My door was locked.
I was inside curled up in fear and, after five minutes, my pursuers gave up.
When they left, I packed up and took the first train to London.
I never came back.
Maybe you call me a weak tear.
But no 18-year-old should be subjected to such a level of intimidation and hostility in an educational institution.
What is even more tragic is that it was Oxford, which has not only formed 14 Conservative party prime ministers but, to this day, hides behind an undeserved reputation of equality and freedom of thought.
