The toughest job in the world: the human mules of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the porters of the Indonesian volcano risk their life and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur through steep stone paths
There are people for whom their job is hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who make a living extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, it has to descend every day to the bottom of its crater, where the sulphurous gas emanating from the bowels of the Earth solidifies upon contact with air.
After pulling out large sulfur rocks, which in total weigh about 70 kilos, he carries them in two bamboo baskets that he carries on his shoulders through steep stone paths.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to 2,386 meters of altitude, but the exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to ascend at turtle pace, keeping the balance and carefully measuring their steps so as not to slip and fall down the cliff.
They know that any mishap could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell down the cliffs of Kawah Ijen years ago.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents for every kilo of sulfur they extract
Once upstairs, they make their way among tourists who photograph them as if they were circus monkeys and, tiringly loading the heavy baskets, walk three kilometers to the scales that a mining company has placed a little lower, at 1,850 meters high.
It is about PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been exploiting the volcano since 1960 and, never better said, its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents) for each kilo of sulfur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, since this mineral is widespread in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
"As usual it is to carry 70 kilos, we take out about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip," explains Anto, who usually carries three daily.
It takes three hours in each and ends up grinding, but they allow you to collect 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems a misery for such an inhuman effort, it is triple what he would earn in the field.
“The miners’ wage is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid at 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day and the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros),” explains the carrier, who previously worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the cut was not so hard, but Anto has returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a reason of weight that, in Indonesia, is as forceful as sulfur: "I married a young woman from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I have brought her to Java."
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto has been playing hard at the Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur has already begun to pass his bill despite covering his face with a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases that the volcano releases.
It is the price you have to pay to achieve your dream.
“I will work two more years because I want to open a store or study Spanish or French,” he promises in more than acceptable English.
Punished for life, this friendly and intelligent young man might be a tour guide, waiter or hotel receptionist, but instead he does the job of a mule.
Sharing a filthy wooden cabin with other porters, he gets up every day at two in the morning because the sulfur does not stop flowing at night, when his characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the middle of the darkness.
Defying the shadows, Anto descends to the crater lighting himself with a small lantern attached to his helmet, which he himself has bought with his money.
Some 400 carriers carry the sulfur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater
Despite its profits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulphur to save costs or supply any equipment to the carriers, who work on their own and at both weight.
In fact, they do not even see part of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) of surcharge per camera that, along with the entrance of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), the guards of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
“This job is for the beasts and not for the people,” protests Madrusin, a 42-year-old carrier who has been at Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school.
Capable of lifting up to 110 kilos, she says she will endure working "as much as she can" because she needs the money to educate her three children, aged between 18 and 10.
I won’t retire, I’ll die here because the volcano has been my whole life
Although sulfur burns the throat and peels the eyes when the wind changes suddenly and traps the miners in the thick columns that come out of the volcano, they are so hard that none of them complains of suffering serious diseases... beyond, of course, their usual respiratory problems, osteoarthritis, knee pains and sores on the shoulders, which have been malformed by the weight.
Swinging the basket on his back, Unainik can now only carry 50 kilos at his 53 years.
Every day, he and his comrades pluck 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks transport to the warehouse in Tamansari, 18 kilometers away along a goat path in the weeds.
“I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life,” proclaims Unainik, opening his mouth well, where he lacks several teeth.
Of his five children, the eldest, 30, also works carrying sulfur.
Time passes, but misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the toughest trades in the world: the one done by the human mules of the Kawah Ijen.
Singapore is looking for babies to save the economy
Singaporeans blame career, stress and the cost of property and education for not having children.
“Singapore’s population needs to grow.”
I am a patriotic husband, you are my patriotic wife, let us fulfill our civic duty and create life!
It may seem implausible that these verses are part of a mint pill ad, but despite that — or perhaps because of that — the video went viral on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
