Many of those ideas may have been creative, but they didn’t necessarily work.
So we thought, why don't we do as creatively as possible to solve this problem, which is to compose a rap?
1.2 Children
The one who does not take it so lightly is the government of Singapore.
It spends $1,300 a year on policies to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for marriages and parents grants up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But all this has had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy and high-tech state city in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leaders and their strict social controls.
Singapore ' s birth rate, according to its national population division, is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2 – known as the replenishment rate – was in 1976.
So why don't Singaporeans have any more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of marriage and family policy at the National Population Division, says it’s due to “better education” and “a wider range of career opportunities.”
“That has allowed people to have a wider range of choices in terms of life goals and priorities, beyond getting married and forming a family,” she explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to increased singleness, and delayed marriage and births, resulting in a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an EU immigration policy aimed at drastically increasing immigration to cope with population decline has created resentment among the local population.
There are websites in Singapore where xenophobia abounds barely disguised against many new immigrants, particularly the Chinese, whom they criticize for keeping wages low and failing to integrate.
The surge in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons Singapore’s ruling party experienced its worst election result since independence last year.
Since the elections there has been an attempt to correct the problem, with higher quotas and levies for foreign workers.
Unexpected Consequences
While the fall in the birth rate has known effects on a nation’s economic growth, tax revenues, health care costs, and immigration policies, Singapore’s example is also having some unexpected consequences.
The government tries not to build so many small houses.
For example, it has begun to affect the real estate sector.
The urban development authority has moved to control the number of small apartments, known as "shoe boxes", that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have surfaces of 46 square meters and have had a lot of sales success.
However, there are concerns that they may promote a bachelor lifestyle and discourage developers who want to build large, family-owned homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of real estate firm EL Developers, says its “shoe boxes” sell much faster than larger units.
They are more popular, in the sense that units run out days, even weeks, faster than larger units.
This makes it much better for our cash flow.
However, he admits that the new rules give clearer guidelines for developers, who were previously hampered if they wanted to offer too many small units in a project.
Too stressed
Singapore is a city-state.
While these new rules may be a step toward increasing the national birth rate, talking to Singaporeans working in the downtown financial district doesn’t seem to have much effect.
“People are very stressed, houses are expensive and so is education, so many people are postponing it,” says one young executive.
Other people may have children.
“But for me it’s important to have my own money and time,” says another 20-year-old.
Men and women mention their career, stress and the cost of property and education as the reasons that prevent them from having children.
So, no matter how much the government tries to push its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, Singaporeans have the last word.
