UNASUR Summit ends without publishing Lima Declaration
The 6th Presidential Summit of the South American Union of Nations (Unasur) concluded today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, previously announced and theoretically signed by the seven presidents attending.
Efe repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the VI Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but sources from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency indicated at the beginning that they would deliver it after the closure, but later said that it will be published at some point on the Peruvian government’s website.
When consulted by the text, they pointed out that the content had been exposed by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, during brief statements to the press.
Journalists’ access to Summit information was restricted at all times.
During the day, only the soundless video of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, audio restricted" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information that circulated among the reporters was delivered by the press spokesmen of some of the Unasur governments attending the meeting, although not the Peruvian one.
The only document released during the day was the list of attending presidents, which caused the discomfort of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more data.
Subsequently, the Peruvian presidency sent an email to the media with the “final declaration” of the summit, but this is Humala’s pronouncement, and not the official document that closed the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the III South America-Arab Countries (ASPA) Summit, and on that occasion, despite being insistently requested by the press, the so-called Lima Declaration that had previously been announced was also not disseminated.
On the official website of ASPA it can be corroborated that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities endeavoured to ensure that transmission systems were insured for all journalists but limited the obtaining of information as much as possible.
The summit also concluded with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to accept a ruling of the Hague Court that settles a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and ratified that they will respect the decision of the (ICJ), which begins Monday in The Hague to listen to the arguments of both parties, in the process that Lima presented against Santiago.
"We will abide by and execute the sentence that defines the differences that we are bringing to this international court today," Humala said, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
“Chile has been, is and will continue to be a country respectful of international law, the peaceful settlement of disputes, treaties and international tribunals,” Piñera said, shaking hands with Humala, alongside the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation by both presidents that they will submit to the ICJ came after Colombia denounced this week the Bogota Pact by which it had agreed to submit to the rulings of that international tribunal, following a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered gravely wrong.
The summit was held with the absence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the removal of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was in charge of opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit, shortly after noon in Lima.
The president read the final document in which he reported that 16 agreements were adopted and the lines of action were set for 31 projects between South American countries for a total of $ 17 billion in investments.
Among the agreements adopted he mentioned that the countries of UNASUR will take "important steps towards the goal of a South American citizenship for which we are expanding the agreements on residence".
It reported that actions are being promoted to improve "cooperation in the fight against citizen insecurity and against transnational organized crime, actions to make medicines more accessible, low-cost internet access in all corners of South America, and jointly and efficiently address the risks of natural disasters."
With a Europe in crisis, “economic consolidation (of Latin America) must not have a triumphalist matrix but must serve to expand our productive matrix and envision a better future for our peoples,” Humala added.
“We have decided to privilege a group of 31 emblematic projects that will improve the connection of South American spaces, especially in rural and border areas ... uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits,” the Peruvian president said in a message read.
Among those projects, he mentioned that five correspond to Peru, and are located on the transversal axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two point to a greater connection with Ecuador, although he did not give more details.
The final document also mentioned the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in that country will serve for his reintegration into the Union of South American Nations," from which he is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated, and good relations between neighbors, was another of the issues highlighted by the summit.
In this regard, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said before starting his participation in the regional meeting that he hoped to meet with his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico to treat in a respectful manner the maritime dispute after a ruling of the ICJ, questioned by Bogota.
"Tomorrow (Saturday) I may have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega," Santos said.
"We are going to review all these paths, they are not exclusive, even the treaty with Nicaragua will require a conversation with Nicaragua," he said.
"With President Ortega, I hope I can tell him to handle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," Santos said.
Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico where they plan to attend the inauguration of the new president of that country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Also, as part of the summit, the bloc’s defense ministers previously met to approve the 2013 Plan of Action, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus on defense in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the latter country is suspended.
Peru holds the pro-tempore presidency of the regional bloc.
