Then, even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye to him "because he brought a cut".
At that time, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
It is now possible to survive this syndrome and do so with quality of life.
However, ignorant of their disease, still many people arrive when the virus has already wreaked havoc, “depleted” their immune system and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the appearance of AIDS in the world, at least of the first reported cases, "the great achievement means at this time that the survival of a patient who initiates treatment in a timely manner and the survival of the general population, is exactly the same," said the head of the HIV Unit of the HCG, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, after saying that this information was endorsed in April of this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectious disease and expert on HIV/AIDS, Andrade Villanueva commented that since 2008, scientists had concluded that AIDS was not a fatal sentence, but the years of survival and quality of life depend on the degree of affectation to the immune system that patients present at the beginning of the diagnosis, with better expectation for those who are not drug users: up to 30 years with a count of 200 CD4 and 50 CD4.
In simple words, the above means that who receives the diagnosis of HIV positive at 25 years of age, under these terms "as long as he stays in control can live without problems until 75 years," explained the interviewee.
To measure this advance, it should be remembered that the life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years on average.
While mortality has dropped significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS dropped from 6,678 cases in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UNAIDS annual report), it is also true that since the onset of AIDS, 60 percent of patients in the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and there are 187 deaths as of May this year; however, universal access to antiretroviral drugs has been assured since 2005.
- Why are there still deaths?
It seems to me that the problem is not access to treatment.
This is how I see it, this is how it happened to us in our hospital.
