Actor Larry Hagman has died.
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth, Texas, became world famous for his central role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R.", in the television series "Dallas", in which he played an unscrupulous, malicious and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as predatory oil tycoon J.R. Ewing on the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in a new season of “Dallas,” died Friday afternoon from cancer complications, according to a family statement provided to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., the Dallas production company.
"Larry was back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, again playing the iconic role he liked most," the family said.
Larry’s family and close friends were with him in Dallas for the Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who played his wife in the original series and sequel, was with Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, her publicist Jeffrey Lane said.
It brought joy to everyone I knew.
He was creative, generous, funny, funny, loving and talented, and I will miss him very much.
"He was an original person and lived life to the fullest," Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with liver cirrhosis in 1992 and admitted to drinking heavily for years.
In 1995, a malignant tumor was found in his liver and he underwent a transplant.
Years before "Dallas", Hagman became famous on television as a decent guy in the light comedy "I Dream of Jeannie", broadcast by NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In it she played Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life is altered when she meets an attractive genius, played by Barbara Eden, and takes her to live with him at his home.
He also starred in two short-lived comedies, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
His film work included critically acclaimed roles in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was his masterful portrayal of the charmingly detestable J.R. that brought Hagman to his highest stardom.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other characters in their orbit aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The promotional phrase “Who shot J.R.?”, designed to generate expectation around an emotional episode in which Hagman’s character is almost killed, generated international speculation and millions of dollars risked in bookmakers.
It also helped give the series an audience record at the time.
When the answer was revealed in a November 1980 episode, an average of 41 million viewers tuned in and made "Dallas" the second most watched entertainment show in history, behind the end of "MASH" in 1983, which had 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law Kristin (played by Mary Crosby) who shot him.
J.R. got her pregnant and then threatened to label her a prostitute unless she left the city, but others also had reason to attack him.
Hagman portrayed Ewing as an insatiable corrupt man with a charismatic smile: a cheating businessman and an unfaithful husband who tried to get his alcoholic wife, Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), interned.
“I know what I want on J.R.’s tombstone,” Hagman said in 1988.
I should say, "Here lies the honest citizen J.R. Ewing."
This is the only deal he lost.
Victoria Principal, co-star of the original series, recalled Hagman on Friday as someone "huge, on and off the screen."
It is unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of admirers in the world, and in the hearts of each of us, that we were lucky enough to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were aired a few months ago with great success for the TNT channel.
Recording of five of the episodes for season two had already been completed and a sixth was in the works, the network reported.
There was no immediate comment from either Warner or TNT on how the series will handle Hagman's loss.
A native of Fort Worth, Texas, he was the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who starred in classics such as "South Pacific" and "Peter Pan".
Martin was still a teenager when she had it in 1931 during her marriage to lawyer Ben Hagman.
He tried his luck on New York theater stages in the early 1950s, and then served in the Air Force from 1952 to 1956 in England.
While there he met the young Swedish designer Maj Axelsson and married her.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and lived for a long time in the Californian city of Malibu, where many celebrities reside.
In 2001 he titled his memoir "Hello Darlin': Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life".
“I didn’t put anything there that I thought would hurt someone or affect them in any way,” he told Associated Press at the time.
After liver transplantation he became an organ donor and volunteered in a hospital to assist fearful patients.
"I advise them, I value them, I meet with them when they come for their surgeries, and then," he said in 1996.
I try to offer some comfort, like “don’t be afraid, it’ll be a little uncomfortable for a short time, but they’ll be fine.”
She was also an anti-smoking activist and participated in several campaigns.
They start a course that explores the "End of the World"
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to teach a course on the end of the world, he knew he had an irresistible hook: The end of the Mayan Calendar’s “long countdown” on December 21, which many people have clung to as proof that the end of the world is coming.
But Charmé had no idea what awaited him in the next couple of months: The cataclysmic Hurricane Sandy, a fiscal cliff some have called “deudarmagedon” and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where end-time Christian theorists believe the Apocalypse will begin.
“I didn’t realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester there has been,” Charmé told students at Rutgers-Camden University in New Jersey this week.
If one analyzes what has been happening in the world today as if we were 30 days away and counting, this has been a really good period.
And remember that bad is good for those of apocalyptic mindset.
And he’s not the only professor offering courses on the “end of the world” this semester, theoretically the last in history.
At Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker is teaching the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
“We analyze why these ideas proliferate over time,” he said, and how they offer hypothetical scenarios that guide certain human behavior.
If nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month students analyzed films with apocalyptic themes and explored how they compare to real-life examples.
“I’ve tried to inform students about what is possible, likely, credible, and impossible,” Vacker said.
On the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, Latin American History professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an adjunct professor of Art History and Anthropology, have teamed up to teach a course, titled just “The End of the World.”
“We didn’t add ‘2012’ to always have the option to teach the course again, in case the world doesn’t end,” Restall said.
Despite “imminent ruin,” students must study, generate projects, and take final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will be taken on the eve of the Apocalypse, leaving students no choice but to work “until the very night the world is supposed to end,” Restall said.
The courses were quite popular.
“It got saturated in two hours,” Restall said of his high-average student course, which was filled with 35 students.
We received emails for weeks and weeks before the start of the semester, from people asking if there was still room.
The students, for their part, assure that the course is one of the most interesting.
“I find it fascinating to see what people are doing to comfort themselves,” said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old career student in Religion and Sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, in Rutgers-Camden.
And it is that the apocalyptic mentality, secular or religious, is only a matter of comfort or the absence of it.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old psychology and nursing graduate student, said he had seen all the apocalyptic movies.
"I've never heard of a class that could teach that," he said.
I'll enjoy it.
But no student interviewed — let alone a professor — said they believed in the expiration date of Dec. 21.
“Our first project was about Mayan prophecy and in a way we discredit it,” said Julie Zeglen, a senior student at Temple, 21, from West Chester.
The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it’s just a key point in the calendar, Restall said.
But he said there is an apocalyptic anxiety in Western culture, dating back several centuries, in which people react to changes around them by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused a spike in this speculation.
“Elsewhere people don’t think about this,” he said.
Mostly in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a religion professor at La Salle University who teaches courses in the Philippines this year, quickly answered the question of whether he knew about any “end-of-the-world” courses there.
“The Philippines does not participate in the end of the world,” he wrote, hinting at an exception from a higher authority.
We have a pardon from the Pope.
Restall noted that over the years there has been talk of many days of the Last Judgment, and said that if nothing happens on December 21, “people will begin to think immediately about the next date” or to philosophize that December 21 is the beginning of a seven-year period at the end of which the world will end.
Students and teachers are taking the date lightly.
Several said they plan to go to "end-of-the-world" parties.
“Maybe I’ll call some friends so we can laugh together,” said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
